To show an error message when `dvdTitle` is empty and `category` is null, you can add a check in the server-side code to return an error response when these conditions are met. Here's an example of how you can modify the server-side code to achieve this:

```javascript
$.ajax({
  type: "GET",
  url: "http://localhost:8081/filmtitle",
  data: {
    dvdTitle: dvdTitle,
  },
  success: function (data) {
    if (dvdTitle == "") {
      sessionStorage.setItem("searchResults", JSON.stringify({ error: "Dvd title is required." }));
      window.location.assign("searchResults.html");
    } else if (category == null) {
      sessionStorage.setItem("searchResults", JSON.stringify({ error: "Select category." }));
      window.location.assign("searchResults.html");
    } else {
      // Rest of the code...
    }
  },
  error: function (xhr, status, error) {
    if (xhr.status == 400) {
      sessionStorage.setItem("searchResults", JSON.stringify({ error: "Invalid request." }));
      window.location.assign("searchResults.html");
    }
  }
});
```

In this code, we've added a check for both `dvdTitle` and `category` being null or empty. If either of them is null or empty, we set an error message in the session storage and redirect the user to the search results page.

In the error response, we're checking if the request was a 400 error (which is typically returned when the request body is invalid). If it was, we set an error message in the session storage and redirect the user to the search results page.

Note that we're using `xhr.status == 400` instead of `xhr.status == 400 && category == null` to avoid a logical error.

